AzurVeda UVeda MFC GUI Release 0.8, 24/02/2007

This application is released under the GNU GENERAL PUBLIC LICENSE Version 2, June 1991 
Read file COPYING. You must read the licenses to understand the following.
  The whole application sources can be found from the website:
http://sourceforge.net/projects/azurvedalib/

This application allows to create and edit AzurVeda contextes with the following class packages :
VedaLib					Which is under the LGPL license and is project native .
VedaLibMath				Which is under the LGPL license and is project native .
VedaLibImage			Which is under the LGPL license and is project native .
VedaLibImageJPEG		Which is under the LGPL license, is project native and is based on lib jpeg-6b, by the independant jpeg group.
VedaLib3DEngine			Which is under the LGPL license and is project native .
VedaLibDemo				Which is under the LGPL license and is project native .
VedaLibSoundMP3			Which is under the GPL license, and based over LibMad http://www.underbit.com/products/mad/

This application is released with 2 executable builders addons, in directories ExeBuilderWindows and
ExeBuilderDreamcast, which both includes elements from the GPL compiler Mingw (a GCC derivate)
 which sources and license terms can be found at:
http://sourceforge.net/projects/mingw/
DreamcastBuilder itself includes elements from KallistiOS, from Cryptic Allusion, 
 which sources can be found at:
http://sourceforge.net/projects/cadcdev/

This is a beta version, but it should be stable. Some functions may have been disabled
or are not finished.

1. What to do with this ?

This is a general context editor. It means You manipulate contextes. 
You can have more than one context at a time, yes that's what is called 
multicontext applications.
A Context is a set of Objects, which are all created from a class 
known by the context. Classes define "kinds" of object. Yes, that's what 
is called Object Programming.
 For example, a Drawing application would know a class "Image", then you
could create many images objects. It could also knows some pencil classes,
 from which you could create pencil objects to draw on the image.
 All applcations are built on this scheme.
 This release was built with classes that allows to create nice visual 
 and sounds. It has 3D object classes, some texture classes to be used,
  a camera viewing class to render the whole thing, end even a MP3 music 
  player class.

 For a first use, we recommand that you familiarize yourself with bass veda
 by throwing the executable, and then use the open icon to load some .avb 
 (avb for AzurVeda Binaries) in the examples directory. 
 As soon as loaded, some objects will automatically be opened in the preview screen.
 You can then try to change values and manipulate objects in the editor.
 The files which names beging with "Demo" are already configured to generate 
 executables: Use Menu item "File/Export Context as Media Executable",
 It will throw a batch script, press a key when the script ends to return to UVeda.
 Executables files should be created in directory Output\ , for each supported
 platforms.

2. How to manipulate the GUI

2A. The context tree class & object browsing:

 When you launch UVeda.exe, a new context is automatically opened.
Note you got one window per context. If you open another context file, 
the old one will still exist under the last context open.
 Each Context window has a tree on the left to browse the classes, 
 which have a Rectangle Icon. Put your mouse upon a class in the tree: 
 A message will explicit the role of each class.
 For example, scroll down to the "Image grey bubble" class, and
 use the right mouse button menu on it: It will propose a "New Object"
 an empty circle item will appear in the tree: it's an object created 
 from the class. It has a default name: BubbleImg0. As it was created, 
 on the upper left of the context window the object definition can be edited: 
 Each objects is defined by a set of members, starting with its name.
  You can modify its members, but you will not see the result yet.
  First, let's preview the object:
  You can do that either by clicking the preview button in the editor, or use
  the "object menu". Pop up the Object menu with the right button 
  on the object circle icon, or in the object edition window.
  this menu has 7 entries: 
    -Preview
    -Preview Previous
    -Edit Preview
    -Edit Previous
    -Clone Object
    -Destroy Object
    -Destroy Independants
 So, just set BubbleImg0 as the previewed object with "Preview"...
 On the lower right part of the context window, you will notice a strange image;
 This is what the "Image grey bubble" does; mathematic image generation.
 Modify the "randomSeed" member of the object definition: the image will change.
 You can notice another thing: the circle item in the tree for object BubbleImg0
 is now blue: It means the object is currently built. Note it does not inform
 if the object is previewed, it inform on its construction state. The previewed object name
 appear near the VCR-Like interface, upon the preview.
 What happened ?
 AzurVeda knows when to construct or unconstruct the objects. if you modify an object
 which is not previewed, nothing will ask the building of the object, and the circle
 will stay empty. Basically, with this application, objects are constructed when previewed.

2B. The Preview screen and the Video Preview Interface

 The Video Preview Interface is there to manipulate the preview of the objects.
 You can use a lots of different classes to create your objects, and most offer a preview
 of what they do. There are 4 red icons in the Preview Interface you can enable
 by clicking them, and then use them by clicking into the preview screen.
  Each icons can be used or not by a class preview.
 The first, the red cross arrows allows to scroll the preview. You can do that with images
 and 3D objects.
 with the middle mouse button you can change depth in 3D preview.
 the second icon is for rotating the preview, and is only used in 3D object preview or in texture preview.
 the third icon change the scale of the display; its behaviour is not finished.
 basically, you scroll the scale of the preview screen with it with the first button,
 and zoom in/out with the middle button. It is useful for equation preview.
  Sometimes, it is possible to trash the preview screen with scale changing, so 
 the fourth icon just reset the position, rotation and scale of the preview (the 3 first icons)
 to their default states.
  
 Some classes define dynamic changes in times, like 3D views or sounds.
 that's why there is a time slider there, and a play/pause/playspeed interface.
 By default, the time slider is between 0 second and 360 seconds, but it
 is possible to change this time scale.( There is currently an interface bug:
 you can only change the values when paused,not in play mode,
  and you got to change the focus with the mouse to validate the time start and end values.
   Don't use return, it does validates the times change there.)

 If you create many objects and preview them, you will notice each ones keeps its
 preview preference: all the red icons stuff and the time management will be kept,
 even after saving, quitting the application, re-throwing it, and reloading.
 You can also come back to previously edited or previewed object with the object
  special menu we've seen. (preview previous, edit previous). 
  Notice all these features are managed by one of the object of the context: 
  the "interface prefs" object. All the preview and time informations for all
   objects are managed and saved by it.
 You can simply destroy it at any time, it will reset the GUI for this context.
 Like any other object, you can use the object menu and do "Destroy Object".
 a new IPref will be of course created as you use the interface.

 2C. Some things to know when editing objects
 
  This is some kind of strange application, interfaces are built automatically
 from object's description, it can explain some strange interface:
 Some classes, like "Media Time Pattern" use lists. Media Time Pattern 
 is a "Media" that mixes other media, 3D views or sounds. It has a first list
 called "Track list", which lists tracks that will be played at the same moment.
 Set the object to preview, and Use icon "+" to add 2 entries.
 To column will be displayed on the left. Now double click one of the list lines,
 and scroll down: another list has appeared ! ( for each lists, double click 
 a line and scroll down to edit the line)
  The second recursive list stands for the media that will be played consecutively
 on this track. add 2 or tree entries to the second list:
 you see that its elements got a time length in seconds, a reference
 to another media to play, and some offset and time speed to edit.
 Double click one of it, and scroll down: you now reach a classic veda
 member edition. the member "Media To Play" offers a "Combo", it is
 a reference combo, and there are a lots of this in other classes.
 a Reference combo describe a reference from an object to another object.
 it is always preset with no reference, but proposes 2 kinds of entries:
 if another objects in the context can be refered, you'll see all their
 names in the combo. After the objects names, some entries begins by "New",
 it is a "New Object" equivalent, for each class types that fits this reference.
 you can perfectly create a new MP3 object from there. Once the reference combo
 is filled, you can choose to edit the refered object with "Go", or only
 set it to preview with "Preview", next to the combo. This allows quick browsing
 between objects. Other strange controls are the tree controls 
 (used by 3D Object Scene for example), that reacts more or less like lists,
 except that when you create a new element with icon "+", it will be created
 under the element that is currently selected.
  An important object member control to know about is the file resource control,
  which you can find in classes "Sound Music MP3 File", "Image File JPEG",
  or "3D Object LWO File". It has a file open icon to search a file, but
  be carefull, for exporting executables, the file path should be relative
  to the executable that will be generated. If you don't like extrenal files,
  you can decide to link the file within the context binary, by ticking "Link In"
  When this tick is set On, the file is loaded once for all and saved with the .avb,
  in that case the filepath is useless. When it is set Off, the disk based file
  is used. 
 Last thing: there are Undo/Redo icons up there in the toolbar. this should work, but
 for the moment, when you destroy a list element or an object, the whole undo
 action stack is flushed, just so you know.
 Be carefull also with the "Flush Name" icon: it empties all object names to zero,
 and undoes will be hardly able to bring names back. This function was made
 to optimize context size before creating executables.

4. Nice File features

 Things you can do with present classes are building 3D objects,
 texts drawn with 3D objects, link objects in 3D scenes,
 make some shape or color shades on the objects with class Object 3D Scene,
 link 3D objects to 3D textures which defines rendering types, images
 to the textures, use Image RGBA Mixer to make more complex images,
 controling camera movements rendering a 3D scene with Media 3D View,
 and save the whole context at any time as a .avb binary.
 
 There comes another aspect of the UVeda Application and of the
 AzurVedaLib API: you can merge any other context file and add their objects
 to your current context using the Open icon with a red cross.
 you can melt 2 contextes this way. So imagine you got an old demo, and
 only want to recover one image, script or anywhat from that demo:
  you simply merge the whole old demo and refers the image from it.
 But, there, you will have a lots of unused objects. 
 How to get rid of them ? 
 We have seen objects can have references to other objects.
 This implies a hierarchy in the objects: a texture will depends on the images
 it refers, and have nothing to do with other images in the context.
 Implicitly, your main media script depends on all the objects it does
 really use, directly or indirectly, by the game of the references.
 So, to flush all unused objects your script doesn't need, use the object
 menu on the script object item, and throw the "Destroy Independant" function.
 All unused objects will be destroyed. (the interface pref object too) 
  This work with any classes of course, you can extract the exact dependant
  object set as a context. Of course you can also clone contextes binaries 
  with "Save As". Using these features makes it very easy to merge the work
  of many people, or recover details of older works.
 
4. How do I create an executable ?

You got a "Export executable" entry in the file menu !
But to make it work, you got to know the following: the executable
created will just play a "media" object. So your context must declare
which is the media that will be the main entry for the executable.
This is done by creating an object with class "Media Access". You should just
have one Media Access object per context to make executables from them.
Note all media objects have an implicit time length that will be used.
 You got to fill the "MainMedia" entry of the access, but you can also fill
 the facultative "bootMedia", which will stand for a little script played
 by the executbale (a progress bar is a good idea) when the main media
 will be created. This bootmedia should length 10 seconds, and the 10 seonds
 will be played during main media time creation.
 We advise that you also give the executable name with "Export Name", this
 name could also be used by the executable code, (for a window title by example)
 
 note the current available media classes are:
  - "Media 3D View"			it allows any 3D rendering.
  - "Sound Music MP3 File"  it plays a MP3 music
  - "Media Time Pattern"   allows the mixing of any media objects.
  
  ... So you can mix 3D rendering and music with a "Media Time Pattern",
  and declare this object as the main entry with a media class object.
  Then, create an executable with the menu.
  
  NOTE: the menu entry "Export Context as Media Executable"
   actually does the following:
  It saves a "demo.cpp" file as would do the "export .c file" entry,
  but then throws create.bat, which is a script that uses compilers
  to actually compile demo.cpp and use a linker to generate executables
  of any type, for any platform. So you may edit create.bat for your own use.

  Note about windows executable generation:
	you can change the icon by changing the file ExeBuilderWindows/Veda.ico 
	the executable compresser UPX is used after compilation because it is GPL,
	 you can change the compressor yourself in create.bat
	 
 
  Note about Dreamcast executable generation: 
	known problems: some transparency behaviours may not be correct in some minor cases,
	when a texture has a nowrite-depth buffer mode.
	try to sort your layers so that they are drawn in a depth order, it should be OK.
    The external file resources loads has not been validated, so
    all files resources for a dreamcast demo should be "linked in" the binary
    with the "link in" tick before generation.
    It currently generates a .elf file and a "unscrambled binary" (ubin)
    file. Dreamcast user will understand that you can upload this files
    with a serial cable and dc-tool on the pc and DCLoad on the dreamcast,
    or use SBI builder, or bootdreams to create bootable CD images...
    (Note create.bat could be patched to do that.)
	When you view a dreamcast demo, reboot with start, or use the 
    analogic pad to manipulate time.
 
 5. That's all folks.

 Note if this application depends on the base package and the MFC, it is not the case
 of the independant base package. Other Editor applications will follow using 
 other GUI APIs, as well as any kind of tools using compatible .avb files.
 
